\begin_layout Standard
By formulation, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{0}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in fact).
 Thus, for any given compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subsetneq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Universal-Approximation-Theorem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 applies.
 However, notice that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 resulting from a desired approximation set and desired approximation accuracy
 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{{\tt p}}$
\end_inset

.
 Surely, for any fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:lemma-ufat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \theta^{\ast}\right\Vert \le\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 However, there is no means of determining this 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Knowing it fundamentally conflicts with the underlying challenge of nonlinear
 regression anyways! Conversely, in practice, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is specified a priori.
 This results in a dilemma.
 The user is force to pick two of the following three: (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{0}$
\end_inset

 function, (2) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be approximated arbitrarily well (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varepsilon}\to0$
\end_inset

), (3) a known bound exists on the weights needed to achieve the desired
 accuracy for the target function.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 must be known to verify the earlier gain conditions since it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, (2) is required.
 Practical use of the developed controller dictates (3) be required.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 may not be ANY continuous function.
 We are forced to the following assumption to resolve the dilemma.
 Fix a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,a number of blocks, width per block, and depth) and a desired accuracy
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varepsilon}_{\text{d}}\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color green
ASSUMPTION.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 belongs to a strict subset of all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{1}$
\end_inset

 functions: those who outputs and first derivatives can be approximated
 arbitrarily well with bounded weights by the chosen ResNet structure.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \varepsilon\right\Vert _{1,\Omega}\triangleq\max_{x\in\Omega}\left\Vert \Phi\left(x,\theta^{\ast}\right)-F\left(x\right)\right\Vert +\max_{x\in\Omega}\left\Vert \left.\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial x}\right|_{\left(x,\theta^{\ast}\right)}-\left.\frac{dF}{dx}\right|_{x}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 It assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\in\mathcal{F}\triangleq\left\{ \mathfrak{F}\in\mathcal{C}^{1}\left(\Omega;\mathbb{R}^{n}\right):\exists\theta^{\ast}\in\mho:\left\Vert \varepsilon\right\Vert _{1,\Omega}\le\overline{\varepsilon}_{\text{d}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, one needs to iterate with both 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 offline on similar systems to the desired application to ensure the above
 assumption is met, albeit heuristically.
 The chosen adaptive update law and initial weights must satisfy an additional
 assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color green
ASSUMPTION.
 The weight update law 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\widehat{\theta}}$
\end_inset

 must be selected to ensure that (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \dot{\widehat{\theta}}\right\Vert \le\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \widehat{\theta}\right\Vert \le\overline{\theta}$
\end_inset

 and (iii) the initial weights and update law must be chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \varepsilon\right\Vert _{1,\Omega}\le\overline{\varepsilon}_{\text{d}}$
\end_inset

 at all times.
 That is, we must start with a good enough approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and the subsequent update law must not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forget
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 this initial knowledge, however poor it may be (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\varepsilon}_{\text{d}}\gg0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, a lack of pre-training (and memory to prevent this 
